DEA is pleased to announce the opening of the David Ellis Academy PreK/GSRP program!

What does this mean?
If you have a child or know of a family that has a child that is four years old, we will be accepting applications starting on FRIDAY!

The PreK/GSRP Program is a free, all-day preschool that will provide quality instruction and meals to 4-year-olds.

Since DEA is operating virtually right now, the PreK classroom will also be virtual, however, once we go back into the building, it would be a full-day program that meets Mon, Tues, Thurs, and Friday, just like the rest of the school.

If you are interested in an application, please complete this prescreening form: https://forms.gle/VhenG8WYM9ATUiUN8

Applications will be sent electronically, beginning this Friday!

FIRST DAY OF SCHOOL 2020/2021!📚

August 30, 2020

Dear David Ellis Academy Families,

Our wonderful administrators, teachers, and support staff have been working extremely hard to prepare their “Virtual” classrooms for our students! They have been working NON-STOP to make sure everything is ready for their first day of online and remote learning.

Online teaching and learning is a new experience for all of us; however, we have been preparing for this new learning environment all summer. Our teachers and support staff have been involved in training since early summer. This training will allow all to be prepared to deliver high-quality teaching…

Join us for our DEA Drive-Thru Promotional Celebration! 🥳

Who: All 8th Graders and their families (in one car) 👩🏽‍🎓👨🏼‍🎓🧑🏽‍🎓
What: Drive-Thru the lot at David Ellis Academy West to celebrate the students and their accomplishments. The students will receive their plaque and certificates at that time.
When: Wednesday, June 10 at 1pm
Where: David Ellis Academy West Campus (Additional instructions will be sent)

***All families are expected to stay in their cars but feel free to decorate the cars and bring signs to support their 8th graders. The student's name will be announced over the loudspeakers as they receive their plaque and certificates.

Thank you for your understanding.

After-school Programing Canceled!

Dear David Ellis Academy Families,

Please be advised that effective immediately the decision has been made to cancel all after-school activities except tutoring, etc. and non-essential gatherings (field trips, basketball games, karate, drum line, dance, etc) until further notice. We will continue to offer morning and afternoon KidZone service until further notice. Parents are asked to make the necessary arrangements to ensure their children are picked up on time at dismissal.

Thank you for your individual efforts to keep our students, staff, and your families safe. Moving forward our school will make determinations foremost on the safety and well-being of students, staff and our entire school community, and with the input of local and state officials. We thank you for your continued support and partnership as we address this situation together.

Best regards,

The David Ellis Leadership Team

Dear David Ellis Academy Families,

I am writing to you today to provide updated information about our plan to address the COVID-19 virus. Please know that our decisions were not made lightly. We realize these difficult decisions have an impact on students, staff, and parents in many ways. We chose to err on the side of extreme caution to best protect the well-being of students and staff. The information included in this email is subject to change as the situation changes in the State of Michigan.

The health and safety of our students and staff is our highest priority therefore, the decision has been made to cancel all after-school activities (except Kid Zone and tutoring)…

DEA FAmily,
>>>>>>> master

As we continue to monitor the Coronavirus' effects on our community, we ask that you continue to do the following:

-Use good hygiene practices to prevent the spread of COVID-19 and other respiratory diseases.
-Stay home if you are sick, and advise others to do the same.
-Always cover coughs or sneezes with a tissue or sleeve.
-Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
-Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands.
-Wash your hands often with soap and warm water for at least 20 seconds.
-Use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol if soap and warm water are not available.
-Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces (computers, keyboards, desks, etc.).
-It’s not too late to get your flu shot! While the influenza vaccine does not protect against COVID-19 infection, it can help keep you healthy during the flu season.

Let's work together to keep our FAMILIES safe!

Good Morning DEA Family!

As we prepare for another awesome school year, we would like to meet with you for a fun, yet, informative Mandatory Family Orientation. This will be held on Friday, August 23 at DEA. You may choose either the 8:30 session or the 12:30 session. We will start in the gym so I can formally introduce myself and the DEA staff will share information regarding the DEA School Culture and what your child will be learning this year. Then, you will be led to your child's classroom to meet the teacher and see your child's learning environment for the 2019-2020 School Year.

A raffle will be held for your chance to win one of three gift cards. DEA T-shirts will also be available for purchase.

Thank you and We look forward to seeing you and your child(ren) on August 23!

~Mrs. Kenya Hildreth and the DEA Leadership Team

Then, you will be led to your child's classroom to meet the teacher and see your child's learning environment for the 2019-2020 School Year.

A raffle will be held for your chance to win one of three gift cards. DEA T-shirts and School Uniforms will also be available for purchase.

Thank you and We look forward to seeing you and your child(ren) on August 23!

Good Day Parents,

Find out how to get your child involved in the summer food program. The Meet Up and Eat Up (or the Summer Food Service Program) is a federal child nutrition program that provides free meals and activities to children 18 and under all summer long when school is not in session with no sign up required. There are over 650 sites (schools, parks, churches, etc.) across the Southeast Michigan region participating in the program and we can help connect folks to their closest MUEU site.

We have engaging Meet Up and Eat Up program literature (available in English, Spanish, and Arabic) and a social media toolkit specifically designed for schools available to help spread the word about this valuable program.

Happy Monday DEA Families,

Here is what to expect as we wrap up the last week of school!

*Monday, June 10 @10am – Kindergarten Promotion Ceremony Rehearsal at DEAW Auditorium (students and staff only)

*Tuesday, June 11 - 8th Grade breakfast and promotion ceremony rehearsal at Greater Grace (students and staff only)

*Wednesday, June 12 @ 2:30pm – Kindergarten Promotion Ceremony at Greater Grace

*Thursday, June 13 @ 1:30pm – 8th Grade Promotion Ceremony at Greater Grace

*Friday, June 14 – Report Cards will be emailed. Cedar Point refunds will be available in the main office. Breakfast and lunch will still be served.

Additional Important Dates:
*Tuesday, June 25 @8:00am – Summer School Begins (for those who reserved their space)

*Thursday, July 19 @ 2:30pm – Summer School Ends

*Friday, August 23 – Family Orientation for the 2019-2020 School Year

*Monday, August 26 – First Day of School for Students

Good Day Parents,

Find out how to get your child involved in the summer food program. The Meet Up and Eat Up (or the Summer Food Service Program) is a federal child nutrition program that provides free meals and activities to children 18 and under all summer long when school is not in session with no sign up required. There are over 650 sites (schools, parks, churches, etc.) across the Southeast Michigan region participating in the program and we can help connect folks to their closest MUEU site.

We have engaging Meet Up and Eat Up program literature (available in English, Spanish, and Arabic) and a social media toolkit specifically designed for schools available to help spread the word about this valuable program.

Children who miss too much school in kindergarten are less likely to read well by third grade. By middle school, absenteeism can predict who will graduate from high school.

A study of weather-related absences in Massachusetts found that each missed day affected a student’s test scores and grades. This was especially true on snowy days when school stayed open but some students missed class.

post_text:
Attendance Works: Weekly Talking Points

There’s not much we can do about the weather, but there are two key steps every parent can take to help avoid absences this year: Make back-up plans for bad weather and keep your children healthy.

It’s important to find a way to get your child to school even when the weather is bad. If you’re having trouble getting to school, reach out to other families, or call the school. It's possible that we can help connect you with families or staff members who can help.

Attendance Works: Weekly Talking Points

This is the time of year when winter weather and children’s illnesses can take a toll on school attendance. But it’s important to get your children to school every day possible.
Absences, even if they are excused, can add up to academic trouble. This is as true in kindergarten as it is in high school.

link:
Talking Points for Families: Support Attendance In the Winter Months

Families are crucial to ensuring students attend school every day whether their role is to transport a young child to school or monitor whether their child is showing up to class. What families say and do has a big influence on their child’s attendance.

As a member of the school community, we'll be engaging and informing parents and guardians about why regular attendance is so important and how quickly a child can fall behind due to too many absences.

Please continue to visit our website and F.B. page to see weekly talking points that could help your family's attendance during these cold winter months.

Dear DEA Families,

As the week's weather forecast has impacted our schedule, our student-led, parent teacher conferences have been rescheduled. Conferences will now take place on Friday, February 15, 2019 from 12:30 p.m. - 6:00 p.m. This will be an early dismissal for students at 11:15 a.m. As the online system will not hold your original time slot due to the date change, you will need to go online and sign in again. The teachers and Mrs. Brown will be available to assist you in making your appointments if needed.

Thank you for your understanding and support in our efforts to conference with you this coming month. We sincerely appreciate your time.

Yours in education,

Ms. Tonette Hardison
